  "prompt": "Can tax exemption be availed on tax saving FD for the entire tenure of 5 years by investing 1.5 lakhs in the 1st year?",
  "response": "No, tax exemption cannot be availed for the entire 5-year tenure of a tax-saving FD just by investing \u20b91.5 lakhs in the first year. Here's why:\n\n*   **Tax Deduction is Limited to the Investment Year:** The tax benefit under Section 80C of the Income Tax Act is available only in the financial year in which you *make the investment*.\n\n*   **Maximum Deduction Limit:** The maximum deduction you can claim under Section 80C in a financial year is \u20b91.5 lakhs.\n\n*   **Interest is Taxable:** The interest earned on the tax-saving FD is taxable according to your income tax slab. This is regardless of whether you claimed a deduction on the initial investment.\n\n**In summary:**\n\n*   You can claim a deduction of up to \u20b91.5 lakhs under Section 80C in the year you invest in the 5-year tax-saving FD.\n*   For the subsequent 4 years, you will not get any further deduction related to that initial investment.\n*   The interest earned on the FD each year will be taxable. Some banks will automatically deduct TDS(Tax Deducted at Source) if the interest income exceeds certain threshold. You must declare this interest income while filing your income tax return.\n\n**Therefore, the correct understanding is:** You get the tax deduction benefit only in the year you invest the money, up to the maximum limit allowed under Section 80C. The investment continues for 5 years, but the tax deduction is not extended over the entire period.",
